I'm going a bit out on a limb here, but I've convinced myself that because the ascent in the index has been so steep, the index is going to take a little while to adjust to the declining median sales price of existing homes, i.e., to plateau and start declining itself. Looking back at the index, it really does appear that the faster (steeper) the change, the more the index tends to be decoupled from and to lag the MSP and to take a little time to come back in sync with it. This is a tricky, unprecedented situation that does not easily lend itself to various modeling methods. Thanks to @JonathanMann, @BayesianChimp, and @erikbays for very useful discussions.

Updating based on the FRED August numbers. I was projecting August to be lower than the 268.62 value. So kudos to @belikewater who came in much closer than me on this per our discussion the other day. Rerunning my 4cast using Winter's Method I obtain results that imply an increased probability for Bin4, so I'm changing my forecast. I went back to the FRED MSP data and found a longer time series dataset for regression, but have abandoned this because of the strong seasonal component in the MSP that increases the error variance in the regression against CSHPI. If I run 3 month moving averages of the MSP I definitely see a slow down there as noted by @JonathanMann. So taking that into account I end up with a slight bias towards Bin4 over Bin3.

Based on the slightly higher than projected August numbers, my model is now projecting September as ~266 and October as ~264. Here are my calculations: The three-month average for August was 360000 which when multiplied by my prediction parameter ("0.000742") would have yielded "267.12". Adjusting this parameter to "0.000745" would have yielded "268.2", still slightly low, but that's as far as I'm willing to move it based on a single observation. With these adjustments in place, the three-month average for September (356,667) multiplied by the "0.000745" parameter yields "265.72". We don't have the median sales price data for October yet, but given the seasonal trends and looking at the past few months, I think it's reasonable to predict that it will be lower than September. With that said, I'll use the September number for October for now. Based on the stated assumptions, the three-month average for October becomes 354,433. When it is multiplied by the "0.000745" parameter, it yields "264.05". Of course, there is a pretty wide range of variation around these estimates, but it appears that we're still most likely to end up in bin 3. Given the fact that @belikewater 's estimates for August were closer than mine though, I'm going to have to update slightly toward his forecast. @LokiOdinevich , @elifland - Any thoughts? Data used to compute three-month rolling averages: https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/HOSMEDUSM052N

The August value is out: 268.616. I had forecast an approximate value of 268.4. 1.384 more to go to end up in bin 4. I think bin 4 is most likely; I think it'll end up just over 271. I think there's some possibility the index could also increase a bit more but not quite reach 270, but I don't think the October value is likely to go below 268. I'm shifting my forecast a little extra strongly towards bin 4 than I probably should, just for fun. (It should probably actually be 30%/70%.) I think this is my final forecast.

@LokiOdinevich , @belikewater , @elifland , @cafebedouin - After additional consideration, a ~10% risk for 250 - 260 is warranted. I had previously been using the noisy metro area data set with weightings to make my estimates, but, switched to this cleaner national data set (also from realtor.com): https://econdata.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Reports/Core/RDC_Inventory_Core_Metrics_Country_History.csv It shows that the median list price fell from 385,000 in July to 380,000 in August and remained flat in September (also 380,000). List prices in this data set do not map exactly to FRED, but this method would put the target FRED number for August / September closer ~262 (about this same level as June), but with a fair amount of wiggle room. Add on to that the fact that October could take another step down and the 250 - 260 bucket looks very possible. With all that said, I still think the arguments @cafebedouin made are probably right, but I'm going to give the 250 - 260 bin some extra weight : https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1347126
I do think bin 4 is more likely, but I hesitate to be so strongly against the crowd and good researchers who have likely investigated this forecast more than I have.

Index at 265.350 on Sept 28. Last month, I forecasted growth of ~4 for July for the forecast index; actual July growth was 4.24. Only 3 months in the forecast. The forecast is becoming constrained. The median sales price (MSP) of existing homes peaked in June and declined gently in July and August. I expect it to continue to decline gently in Sept and Oct. As a consequence, I'll expect the forecast index, which is a 3-month moving average of data related to the MSP of existing homes, to increase by ~3 for Aug, ~2 for Sept and maybe ~1 for Oct. https://ycharts.com/indicators/us_existing_home_median_sales_price Suppose growth in the index for each month: Aug 4, Sept 4, Oct 3 => 276.35 (a very unlikely maximum scenario) Aug 4, Sept 3, Oct 3 => 275.35 Aug 3, Sept 2, Oct 2 => 272.35 Aug 3, Sept 2, Oct 1 => 271.35 (an approx scenario I think most likely) Aug 3, Sept 2, Oct 0 => 270.35 Aug 3, Sept 0, Oct 0 => 268.35 Aug 2, Sept 0, Oct -1 => 266.35 Aug 1, Sept -2, Oct -2 => 262.35 (an extremely unlikely minimum scenario) Only bins 3 and 4 are realistic. I think the index is likely to be approx 271 to 272, or with a wider margin, 270.35 to 274.35. Unfortunately, that is close to the boundary between bins.

June value: 260.866. Increase of 5.568 over May. Still a really big increase. The Index has a seasonal trend of enhanced increases from March through July that start to taper off in August and declines after that, until the following March. This trend is superimposed on overall growth of the index and can be seen even in 2020 and 2021, except that growth didn't decline at the end of the summer in 2020. Will we see a decline in growth through the end of summer in 2021? One factor in favor of a decline in growth is that the economy is gradually returning to pre-pandemic activities; one factor against this is that new housing construction has faced shortages, and these bottlenecks may push more people into purchasing existing housing stock who would otherwise have purchased new homes. (No new homes are included in this Index.) This feels like a bubble that will gradually pop as people have to go back to the office and won't want to commute to their suburban dream houses. But I don't think the bubble is likely to pop before October, especially as a lot of people continue to telecommute and high levels of Covid spread continue. And also, there is generally a housing crisis in the US, so in the end, maybe it will simply be a gradual slide rather than pop. Also, the median home sale price is starting to plateau (https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/MSPUS), which can be a leading indicator for the forecast Index (see, e.g., 2005). A risk to consider is that we'll see a decline in the median home sale price for Q3 like that seen in Q3 of 2006; this corresponded to a fall of about half a point in the forecast index. However, as the median home sale price grew ~5% for July, I don't think a substantial decline in the median home sale price for Q3 or any decline in the forecast index is likely in the forecast period. But it is clear that the housing market is approaching some kind of peak. So I'll expect another month of growth of ~5 pts/month for July, followed by a bit less growth in August and a little less in September and October, but I'll allow for the possibility that growth will continue at existing levels for July through October. Looking at 2020, I don't think avg growth >5 pts/month is out of the question, but I don't think 2021 will be like 2020 because the median home sale price was exploding in Q3 2020 but is starting to plateau now. Possible outcomes are constrained by time at this point. Only 4 months of data remaining in the forecast. I think growth in home prices is likely to return to trend in the coming months. Home prices really jumped up, and I've heard much of the reason for that is that the supply of houses on the market cratered. Checking out some data on that [1] it looks like that's exactly right. Housing supply cratered in late spring/early summer 2020. That coincides with the beginning of the above-trend increase in housing prices according to the Case-Shiller metric [2]. As shown in [1], as of May the housing supply is back into the territory from before the pandemic. So I think it's likely that prices level off or return to trend soon. High prices incentivize home-owners to get their houses on the market and they also disincentivize buyers from buying at outrageous prices, and both these factors will put downward pressure on home prices.

So, an April data point actually includes data from Feb. through April. https://www.economy.com/home/products/samples/case-shiller-FAQ.pdf * Data for the S&P/Case-Shiller Index are currently available only through April 2021. * The median home sales price fell a little in Q1 2021: https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/MSPUS * Because S&P/Case-Shiller Index data are 3-month moving average data, this index generally lags median home sales prices.

April 2021 is 249, and the price growth rate has accelerated for each of the past 4 months. It's been increasing 1-2% MoM for about 8 consecutive months and supply is still low. Pre-COVID MoM price growth rate was 0.4%. The conservative MoM growth rate of 0.4% gets us to 255 in October 2021. 1% MoM gets us to 264, and 2% MoM growth gets us to 280. None of the data available shows the recent effect of potential homebuyers balking at the skyrocketing prices though.
The index has moved 40 points in the last 6 months and us now at about 248. At this pace it would move 20 points by October, putting it at about 268.
